<DOC id="NYT_ENG_20101123.0028" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
BRONCOS NEED NEW (YOUNG) BLOOD
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
SAN DIEGO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
From the mess that was an ugly 35-14 defeat, Denver
safety Brian Dawkins walked through the debris of a cramped locker
room, leaving behind another lost Broncos season with his head held
high.
</P>
<P>
"I'm going to continue to fight. That's just what I do,"
Dawkins said Monday.
</P>
<P>
But watching Dawkins give futile pursuit to the San Diego
Chargers, it felt like the end is near.
</P>
<P>
Is Dawkins done? Have the years finally stolen his talent?
</P>
<P>
"It's just a frustrating thing when you're out there on the
field and you start thinking too much," Dawkins said, after nearly
all of his teammates had already departed for the team bus.
</P>
<P>
Under a haunting moon, with a chill rolling in from the Pacific
Ocean, what can make even a strong man shudder is the slow
realization that time eventually beats us all.
</P>
<P>
There's a Hall pass waiting for Dawkins in Canton, Ohio. He is
one of the fiercest safeties to ever play in the league.
</P>
<P>
But Dawkins tackled nothing except air as millions of witnesses
saw on "Monday Night Football." He personified the ineptitude of
a defense that was too slow, too old and too vulnerable to keep the
Broncos in a road game that was their final failed chance to make
the playoffs a relevant issue in Denver as the NFL season gets
serious.
</P>
<P>
It makes zero sense for a team surrendering 28.7 points per game
to employ seven starters over the age of 30. Change is inevitable.
The defense must be rebuilt.
</P>
<P>
In a position to put the wood to San Diego receiver Patrick
Crayton late in the second quarter, Dawkins swung and missed, with
his mistake resulting in a 40-yard touchdown that allowed the
Chargers to take a 14-point lead to halftime.
</P>
<P>
"I've got to make that play," Dawkins said.
</P>
<P>
With the same helplessness as chasing lost youth, Dawkins was
made to look old and inadequate on a short pass turned into a
57-yard touchdown by Darren Sproles that shattered the already
fragile spirit of the Broncos on San Diego's opening possession of
the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
Asked if it was tougher to get a grip on Sproles as a 15-year
veteran than a player in his prime, Dawkins definitely said,
"Nah."
</P>
<P>
When he took the job as Broncos coach, Josh McDaniels promptly
hired Dawkins as a free agent, investing a five-year, $17 million
contract in the longtime Philadelphia star. Despite obvious
indications the Eagles thought one of the most beloved players in
their franchise history was well past his prime, McDaniels believed
Dawkins still had the right stuff to intimidate on the field and
lead in the locker room.
</P>
<P>
But, if anything, McDaniels listens too much to the football
ideals in his heart to the extent that it blinds the young coach to
the harsh realities on the game film. Why give up on Peyton Hillis
because he was an imperfect fit for the offensive scheme? What's
the practical impact of spending a first-round draft choice on a
quarterback who's a project, when the Broncos needed immediate
help? Where's the logic constructing a defensive secondary in which
every starter rolls on at least 30-year-old legs?
</P>
<P>
This dangerous naivete in the approach to building a team is
what could eventually get McDaniels fired in Denver. What the
Broncos wanted was the player Dawkins used to be, which unburdened
the team from the cost-effectiveness analysis of how many big hits
the safety had left in his aging body.
</P>
<P>
What McDaniels must do in the final six meaningless games
remaining on the Denver schedule is somehow sell his vision of the
future to disheartened players, an owner who must suffer yet
another season without a playoff berth and disgruntled
Broncomaniacs.
</P>
<P>
It's hard to see how that future includes Dawkins.
</P>
</TEXT>
