<DOC id="NYT_ENG_20101101.0133" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
BC-DOW-DET
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Dow Chemical stock rises as demand, investment grow

      By Jaclyn Trop
      The Detroit News
</P>
<P>
Midland - Dow Chemical Co. is emerging from the recession and a
failed joint venture in Kuwait as a stronger, more innovative
company, corporate officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Renewed consumer demand in the United States and abroad, growth
in emerging markets and investing billions of dollars in research
and development will carry Dow into the future, leading to strong
year-over-year gains in 2011 and 2012, Chief Executive Andrew
Liveris said at a Monday press conference.
</P>
<P>
"We are literally bursting at the seams with new projects and
innovation," Liveris said.
</P>
<P>
Joint ventures with national governments and higher profit
margins on products and technologies are also bolstering the
chemical company's growth.
</P>
<P>
Dow has changed its perspective on meeting consumer demand, said
Mike Gambrell, executive vice president of manufacturing and
engineering.
</P>
<P>
"Historically, we worked inside out," Gambrell said. "Now
we're going out and learning what our customers need first."
</P>
<P>
But innovation remains at the forefront of Dow's growth
strategy. Dow's performance division is on track to file for 190
patents this year, up significantly from 2009.
</P>
<P>
"We're definitely on an uptick," said Ganesh Kailasam, the
division's vice president of research and development.
</P>
<P>
These development have led the company's stock price to surge 21
percent since early August, when a lower-than-expected profit for
the second quarter led to a 10 percent drop in the stock price. The
stock, which closed at $25.50 a share on Aug. 3, closed Monday at
$30.87.
</P>
<P>
The firm did better than analysts expected in the third-quarter,
when revenue grew 7 percent and earnings fell because of one-time
charges, according to results released last week.
</P>
<P>
A major Dow product release is scheduled for mid-2011 when its
Dow Solar division brings its solar shingles to market. The
shingles reduce or offset a household's energy consumption.
</P>
<P>
"Residential rooftops are the perfect canvasses to harvest
energy from the sun," said Dow Solar general manager Jane
Palmieri. Dow expects the shingles to act as a "badge of honor"
when homeowners install them, she said.
</P>
<P>
jtropdetnews.com
</P>
</TEXT>
