<DOC id="NYT_ENG_20101120.0002" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
UNIVERSITY OF COLORADO MUST CAREFULLY SELECT NEW ARCHITECT OF FOOTBALL PROGRAM
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The University of Colorado's selection of a new football coach
could be the school's most critical hire since 1917 when architect
Charles Klauder was chosen to design a unique master plan for the
Boulder campus.
</P>
<P>
CU must seek a similar visionary who will develop a successful
and unique plan for the future of Buffaloes football.
</P>
<P>
As the university's football program has gone from the
"scorched earth" Dan Hawkins claimed he inherited to a colossal,
meteor-sized crater he left beneath the Flatirons, it confronts a
new era, new financial difficulties, another new reconstruction and
rejuvenation and a new conference.
</P>
<P>
The Buffs need a winner.
</P>
<P>
They can't join the Pac-12 on a hope and a dare and a weak
coach.
</P>
<P>
Athletic director Mike Bohn understands fully his long-term
employment depends on the pick, and Colorado president Bruce Benson
and Boulder chancellor Phil DiStefano know how important the first
football coach chosen during their charge is to CU, fundraising and
their reputations.
</P>
<P>
So those three and the selection (advisory) committee -- composed
of the faculty's athletic representative, the school's CFO, an
interim vice chancellor, a professor and three prominent boosters
who are CEOs of major companies -- can't afford (figuratively and
literally) another Hawkins Blunder.
</P>
<P>
At least 20 candidates have been considered, discussed and
investigated; several have been contacted directly or indirectly; a
few already have been invited for interviews, and the number has
been shortened to A, B and C lists.
</P>
<P>
Although Bohn, who will make the final pronouncement, said this
week he will not comment again on any contenders, it is known he
has received hundreds of calls from candidates' supporters and
lobbyists (including NFL coaches) and personal pleas for the
position from prominent college coaches.
</P>
<P>
Despite what many believe, this is a highly sought job, and it
could pay more than most believe.
</P>
<P>
The speculated or confirmed candidates' list includes former
head college coaches (Bill McCartney and Mike Bellotti), ex-NFL
coaches (Mike Nolan and Jon Gruden), current college head coaches
(Air Force's Troy Calhoun, Houston's Kevin Sumlin, San Diego
State's Brady Hoke and Georgia's Mark Richt), college assistants
(Auburn's Gus Malzahn, Alabama's Jim McElwain, Oklahoma's Brent
Venables, Nebraska's Shawn Watson and Florida State's Mark Stoops),
NFL assistants (Eric Bieniemy and Jeremy Bates), high school
coach/Broncos broadcaster Dave Logan and interim CU coach Brian
Cabral.
</P>
<P>
Mike Leach, Mike Price and Mark Mangino also have been
mentioned, but CU has ruled them out because of past controversies.
</P>
<P>
And, almost a month ago in a column recommending that Hawkins
resign, I first brought up one more name.
</P>
<P>
"Les Miles of LSU probably could be lured to CU. Miles and LSU
have just about had enough of each other, and the coach of the 2007
BCS champions has said to friends that his favorite place to live
and coach was Boulder, where he served as offensive line coach
under McCartney from 1982-86. Would the 'Mad Hatter,' so-named
because of his dicey play-calling and odd nature, be the first
choice as Les 'Miles High'?"
</P>
<P>
I stand by that statement, which has been widely circulated, and
commented on, in Louisiana and throughout the SEC. Despite a 9-1
record this season at LSU, so many people in that state want Miles
fired. He receives about $3.8 million per year, but his only exit
buyout is if he goes to Michigan.
</P>
<P>
DiStefano is on record saying he favors "a coach who is either
successful now as a head coach or has recent coaching experience
either with someone from the Pac-12 or the Big 12, somebody in a
conference similar to, if not equal to, the conference that we're
joining."
</P>
<P>
Several head or assistant coaches would fit the criteria.
Minnesota Vikings coach Brad Childress said Friday he had been
contacted by the search committee about Bieniemy, his running-backs
coach. Bieniemy played and coached at CU and also has been a UCLA
assistant.
</P>
<P>
Bellotti -- former Oregon coach, then athletic director -- and
McCartney, who guided the Buffs to their only national
championship, say they have been approached by CU to gauge their
interest.
</P>
<P>
The coordinators at Auburn, Alabama and Oklahoma probably would
qualify but haven't been head coaches. Nebraska's Watson was a head
coach and served as an assistant at CU but insists he's not a
candidate. Houston's Sumlin was the offensive coordinator at
Oklahoma, but one mark against him is he took an assistant's job
with CU in January 2003 but resigned a month later.
</P>
<P>
Is Calhoun in a conference "equal to"? The Mountain West's TCU
is ranked third in the BCS poll.
</P>
<P>
Bellotti and McCartney (who both have many backers and as many
detractors), Bieniemy and Sumlin (African-Americans), Logan (who
has never served on a college staff but played at CU and in the NFL
and has won five state high school titles, three at Mullen) and
Cabral (who played at CU and in the NFL and has been on staff in
Boulder since 1989) likely will get interviews.
</P>
<P>
One member of the search committee, George Solich, began efforts
months ago to entice 50 superboosters to contribute $1 million each
to the football program. The dormant idea will be revived with the
firing of Hawkins and the switch to the Pac-12. A $50 million
influx will greatly aid CU in wading out of debt caused by the
moves.
</P>
<P>
The process should be rather speedy, given the research already
done, the narrowing of the candidates, the interview process and
the NCAA regulations which allow coaches' visits to recruits' homes
starting on Dec. 1.
</P>
<P>
The coach ultimately selected has to be as triumphant on his
field as Charles Klauder was in his field. Klauder was a great
hire. His "Tuscan vernacular" created an everlasting legacy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="NYT_ENG_20101107.0005" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN NAVY DRIVES OUT GANGS IN TOURIST-ORIENTED BORDER TOWN
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
NUEVO PROGRESO, Mexico 
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
On fall and winter weekends, droves of
Rio Grande Valley residents and American snowbirds still cross the
Rio Grande here, drawn by the $1 cold Coronas, $1.50 shoe shines,
$4 haircuts, $15 tooth extractions and cut-rate prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
For the bolder, bargains on plastic surgery and dental implants
are also available.
</P>
<P>
While American tourists are quickly becoming extinct elsewhere
along the Mexican border because of alarming travel advisories and
narco violence, this shopper's Mecca continues to pack them in.
</P>
<P>
This year, more than 1 million pedestrians and almost as many
motorists are expected to cross the bridge to shop and dine in this
town of 15,000 just a few miles south of Weslaco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
"No U.S. or Canadian citizens have been endangered in anyway,"
claims the town's upbeat website, which also boasts that Nuevo
Progreso "is the safest place to cross the Mexico border."
</P>
<P>
And indeed, with violence raging to the east in Matamoros, and
upriver in Reynosa and Nuevo Laredo, this bazaar of bridge urchins
begging for change, politely insistent sidewalk vendors and
jam-packed curio shops exists as an island of border tranquility.
</P>
<P>
"Oh my God, I wouldn't even consider going to Matamoros," said
Joann Anderson, 63, of Huntsville, Texas, visiting with her husband
Thomas. "I love coming here. We come for the dentistry, to get
glasses and to buy antibiotics and hormones. I feel safe here."
</P>
<P>
Only one violent incident has occurred, a shootout in December
that left two dead. But beneath the almost quaint, throw-back
ambiance of tourist-friendly Mexico is another story.
</P>
<P>
For the past two years, a criminal organization has operated
here, extorting and kidnapping local businessmen with impunity.
</P>
<P>
Not until the arrival of marines from the Mexican Navy early
last month were the gangsters, who had shown no fear of the state
police or Army soldiers prominently stationed at the bridge, chased
from town.
</P>
<P>
"It was invisible. The tourists didn't know anything about the
extortions," said one dentist who asked not to be named. "Some of
the bars closed because of the extortions, and I'm sure there were
kidnappings."
</P>
<P>
A medical doctor said the existence of the extortion racket was
widely whispered but never talked about openly because of fear.
</P>
<P>
"The town was full of secretive voices. But no one would ever
say, 'I'm paying.' Everyone was scared," he said, also asking not
to be named. "It never touched me. I don't know who they were."
</P>
<P>
One local businessman agreed to talk about the racket on the
condition he not be identified. He said he paid at least $25,000 to
the gangsters over two years and lost most of his businesses.
</P>
<P>
"Two years ago, everything was perfect here. We knew the drug
gangs existed, but they didn't bother us here," he recalled in a
recent interview.
</P>
<P>
That changed around Thanksgiving 2008, when some armed men asked
him to take a ride with them in an SUV. When the trip was over, he
had new business partners and their terms were clear and harsh.
</P>
<P>
"They told me I had to pay $5,000 up front for each of my three
businesses, and $500 a month after that. They didn't threaten me.
They just said pay up or you know what will happen," he recalled.
And for nearly two years, he was slowly starved out of business.
</P>
<P>
"Young guys, about 18 years old, would come around and say,
'I'm here for the 'quota,' and if I didn't have it, I knew I would
have to close. We never knew who they were, the Zetas, La Familia,
the Gulf Cartel or someone else," he said.
</P>
<P>
In quietly comparing notes with others, he learned who else was
being extorted.
</P>
<P>
"All the bars were paying, and some of the pharmacies," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Eventually, the extortion and a depressed economy forced him to
close all but one of his businesses. He said he made his last $500
payment about a month ago, just before the dramatic arrival of the
Navy.
</P>
<P>
Others, whom he knows personally, fared even worse.
</P>
<P>
"A lot of important people were forced to leave. Some other
people were kidnapped. They charged $1 million or $1.5 million to
let them go," he added.
</P>
<P>
When the Navy arrived in force in early October, the
extortionists vanished.
</P>
<P>
"They came in with three helicopters and about 200 marines. Not
a shot was fired. They knew exactly where to go to get these
guys," he said. "They rounded up all the police, everyone
pertaining to the police. They grabbed the people who were charging
the quotas. And now they are in charge."
</P>
<P>
At one of the dozens of pharmacies on the main drag offering
bargains with few strings attached, such as $4.95 for a bottle of
120 Prilosec pills, a store clerk in a white smock explained why
the owner was absent.
</P>
<P>
"Like the others, he moved across to the other side. People
told me he had been threatened. He's been gone for more than a
year. A lot of people with money left," he said, declining to give
his name.
</P>
<P>
"All the businesses were paying quotas. It ended when the
marines came."
</P>
<P>
When the marines arrived, they went door-to-door handing out
fliers that read: "Enough! Don't allow more robberies,
kidnappings, corruption or violent acts against your family. The
Navy has no pacts with criminal organizations. We are here to serve
our Mexican society."
</P>
<P>
Included was a phone number and e-mail address to anonymously
denounce the criminals.
</P>
<P>
Contacted at their base in Progreso, Navy officials declined to
comment on their operation.
</P>
<P>
Alfonso Trevino, president of the local chamber of commerce and
the owner of a building materials company, was one of the few here
who agreed to talk on the record.
</P>
<P>
He attributed a 30 percent drop in tourist visits over the past
several years, and the failure of some businesses, to multiple
factors. It began with a change in U.S. policy toward requiring a
passport for returning Americans that killed off the youthful
night-time drinking crowd.
</P>
<P>
Added to this, he said, were the swine flu scare of 2009, the
U.S. financial crash of 2008, and the continuing "insecurity"
problem in northern Mexico.
</P>
<P>
But, Trevino said, even though he heard plenty of rumors, he had
no direct knowledge of an organized crime group operating in town.
</P>
<P>
"They never approached me for money. The ones targeted were the
bars. I've also heard rumors of kidnappings," he said. "What
happened here is nothing compared to what happened elsewhere. The
main reason for the failed businesses is the drop in tourism."
</P>
<P>
Some signs indicate that the town's season of torment may be
ending.
</P>
<P>
On a recent Saturday, the parking lot on the U.S. side of the
river was full of cars, some bearing license plates from Minnesota,
North Dakota, Illinois and Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
Along Avenida Benito Juarez, the sidewalks were jammed with
tourists dodging vendors who hawked everything from diced cactus to
gold crowns to male virility pills. It was almost like the good-old
days.
</P>
<P>
"I think with the arrival of the Navy, the fear will go away.
We are a city that depends 100 percent on the United States. When
the rumors die down, the people will return," said a medical
doctor, who asked not to be named. "I'm seeing patients I haven't
seen in eight months. Now they are coming back," he said.
</P>
<P>
Some tourists who never quit coming say Nuevo Progreso remains a
unique and charming window to Mexico, perhaps the last one
available to Texans.
</P>
<P>
"We've been coming for 15-20 years, about once a month. It's
real pleasant.
</P>
<P>
I tell people about it all the time," said Mike Saguaw, 52, a
school teacher from San Antonio, visiting with his two sons, wife
and sister-in-law.
</P>
<P>
While the family waited for lunch to be served at a modest
sidewalk cafe, his wife bought fresh tortillas and a bag of pork
rinds.
</P>
<P>
"We've seen a lot of change for the good. And we've never seen
any violence here," he said. "We buy a bottle of tequila . . .
and eat chicharones all the way home."
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC id="NYT_ENG_20101111.0086" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
ANTI-DEFAMATION LEAGUE CRITICIZES BECK FOR SOROS REMARKS
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Fox News host Glenn Beck was criticized by the Anti-Defamation
League, a leading Jewish advocacy organization, on Thursday in
response to a televised segment about financier George Soros and
the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
Throughout three programs this week, Beck has portrayed Soros, a
billionaire investor and philanthropist, as a "puppet master" who
is "notorious for collapsing economies and regimes all around the
world" and whose "next target" is America. Citing Soros'
statements about the decline of the dollar, Beck said, "Not only
does he want to bring America to her knees, financially, he wants
to reap obscene profits off us as well."
</P>
<P>
Abraham Foxman, national director of the Anti-Defamation League,
took issue with Beck's depiction of Soros as a "Jewish boy helping
sending the Jews to the death camps," calling it "offensive" and
"horrific."
</P>
<P>
On his Fox program Tuesday, watched by about 2.8 million people,
Beck said that during the Holocaust, the 14-year-old Soros "used
to go around with this anti-Semite and deliver papers to the Jews
and confiscate their property and then ship them off."
</P>
<P>
Beck continued: "I am certainly not saying that George Soros
enjoyed that, even had a choice. I mean, he's 14 years old. He was
surviving. So I'm not making a judgment. That's between him and
God." He also said that "many people" would call Soros "an
anti-Semite," although "I will not."
</P>
<P>
Fox stood by Beck. Joel Cheatwood, a senior vice president at
Fox News, said in a statement Thursday afternoon that the
"information regarding Soros' experiences growing up were taken
directly from his writings and from interviews given by him to the
media, and no negative opinion was offered as to his actions as a
child."
</P>
<P>
Still, Foxman asserted that Beck's invoking of the childhood
experience was "unacceptable," adding, "To hold a young boy
responsible for what was going on around him during the Holocaust
as part of a larger effort to denigrate the man is repugnant."
</P>
<P>
Beck has sparked controversy in the past for repeatedly invoking
the Holocaust and Nazi Germany. But some Jewish leaders have backed
him up in the past, and Tuesday, Beck said he was "probably more
supportive of Israel and the Jews than George Soros is."
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
